{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/408"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"408"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31888"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"385"},{"type":"tags","id":"904"},{"type":"tags","id":"934"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"3813"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5772"},{"type":"tags","id":"9118"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5643"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12424"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37006"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42077"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43797"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47140","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/47140"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 78-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a four-week history of increasing constipation associated with crampy abdominal pain and distension. Prior to this this she  has no history of abdominal pain but has noticed some weight loss and fatigue. Her surgical history includes an appendicectomy and a hysterectomy. She takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 134/84 mmHg, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Her conjunctiva are pale and her abdomen is uniformly distended and there is mild widespread tenderness. The bowel sounds are increased and high-pitched. Her rectum is empty and no abnormalities can be palpated on digital rectal examination. An abdominal X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Caecal volvulus","Pseudo-obstruction","Adhesive-obstruction","Carcinoma of the sigmoid colon","Sigmoid volvulus"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has had a recent change in bowel habit, suggesting something causing progressive luminal occlusion. In her age group, colonic malignancy must be excluded and is the most likely explanation for her symptoms. The diagnosis is given away by the radiological pattern of gas distribution - distended colon with a cut-off in the region of the sigmoid colon and no gas in the rectum. Whilst non-malignant sigmoid lesions or strictures such as in severe diverticulitis could present in such a way, this patient most likely has a \u003Cstrong\u003Ecarcinoma of the sigmoid colon\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdhesional obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Ecaecal volvulus\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Esigmoid volvulus\u003C/strong\u003E tend to be acute events, with symptoms usually only appearing a day or two at most before the increase in their severity leads the patient to seek medical help.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPseudo-obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E usually has a clearly defined precipitating cause such as recent surgery or retroperitoneal trauma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["An unexplained change in bowel habit in an older patient should always raise the possibility of malignancy."],"references":["Brenner H, Kloor M, Pox CP. Colorectal cancer. Lancet 2014;383:1490-1502. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24225001/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31888"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"408"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14509"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14509","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14509"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2cf8b8a6-bc34-404d-92b3-b57172700b68.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2cf8b8a6-bc34-404d-92b3-b57172700b68.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":367,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31888","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/31888"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-16T22:19:39+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-27T08:00:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"408"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47140"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"hea